Ask a doctor: Is there a treatment that reverses balding?             Hillary Orinde  27th Apr 2020 07:40:00 GMT +0300 Hillary Orinde  27th Apr 2020 07:40:00 GMT +0300 Hillary Orinde      Dr Winnie Njenga, a dermatologist at Kiambu Level 5 Hospital, answers some of the most frequently asked questions around skincare. Pick up skin protection tips, discover some of the common skin problems and learn what suspicious growths might mean.  After I turned 30, I developed acne. I have never had to deal with that before. What can I do? How does one deal with adult acne?   I have skin tags; many of them. And I don’t like them. Is there anything I can do to slow down their development?   What are the most common skin problems you deal with?  For More of This and Other Stories, Grab Your Copy of the Standard Newspaper.   Read Now » For More of This and Other Stories, Grab Your Copy of the Standard Newspaper.   Read Now » Read Now »  My father had male-pattern baldness. I am almost 35 and noticed that my hair is not growing back quite as thick anymore. Is there anything I can do to prevent it?   I just turned 34 and want to get onto a holistic self-care path. Do I need to be on supplements?   Collagen supplements or collagen topical creams; which ones do I go for?   I work in a high-stress job and I do have a good diet and take care of my skin. But I still have acne.   I have tried all lip balms, even medicated ones, to heal my perpetually dry lips. What do you advise?   I am on a hormonal contraceptive and I suspect that it is the cause of my suddenly problematic skin. Short of stopping the usage, what are some of the tips you could share that would help my skin?   As a dermatologist, what is your opinion on clean beauty?   I am only 28 and already sporting some grey strands of hair. My dad and mum didn’t get theirs at such a young age. What could be the problem?   Are eye creams necessary or are they just glorified moisturisers?   All the commercial sunscreens I have tried out